{{Main|Kingdom of Polonnaruwa}}
{{History of Sri Lanka}}
The '''Polonnaruwa period''' was a period in the history of Sri Lanka of the [[Kingdom of Polonnaruwa]] from 1056 to 1236. The period begins after the  [[Chola conquest of Anuradhapura]].

The [[Kingdom of Polonnaruwa]] was the second major [[Sinhalese People|Sinhalese]] kingdom of Sri Lanka. It lasted from 1055 under [[Vijayabahu I]] until 1212 under the rule of [[Lilavati of Sri Lanka|Lilavati]]. The Kingdom of Polonnaruwa came after the [[Anuradhapura Kingdom]], which was invaded by [[Chola]] forces under [[Rajaraja I]]. It also followed the [[Kingdom of Ruhuna]], in which the Sinhalese Kings ruled during Chola occupation.

[[Vijayabahu I of Sri Lanka|Vijayabahu I]] (1055–1110), recaptured the whole Island and established [[Polonnaruwa]] as the new capital. King Vijayabahu married a second queen from the [[Kalinga (province)|Kalinga]] ([[Orissa, India|Orissa]]) Royal Family, and had a son, [[Vikramabâhu I of Sri Lanka|Vikramabâhu I]], and a daughter, [[Ratnavali]]. His sister, [[Mitta of Sri Lanka|Mitta]], married a [[Pandya]] Prince who had three sons. His eldest son, Manabharana, married Ratnavali. Their son was [[Parākramabāhu I of Sri Lanka|Parākramabāhu I]] (1153–1186) Grandson of Vijayabahu I, Prince of [[Sinhala people|Sinhala]]-[[Pandyan]]-[[Kalinga (province)|Kalinga]] descent, son of Manabharana and Vijayabahu’s sister, Mitta. He was a very powerful king who was noted for his engineering,<ref>Broheir, R. L. (1937) ''Ancient Irrigation Works in Ceylon''. 3 vols.</ref> naval power, art, culture, Sinhala inscriptions, and even a Tamil edict in Uruthota ([[Kayts]]). The [[Chulavamsa]] was written by Dharmakirthi, updating the [[Mahavamsa]] to include Parakramabahu.

